The Wait Is Over! We’re excited to announce our Musical Theater Masterpiece “Hii Ni Afrika” will be showcasing next weekend on 12th and 13th of August at the National Museum Of Tanzania (Opposite IFM college in Dar es Salaam).

There will be two shows  per day.  One from 2pm-3pm and the other from 7pm-8pm. Please note, Saturday 7pm - 8pm show is invitees only. 

Book your ticket now! Either text your full name, date and show time you would like to attend 0744067433 or register through 
https://bit.ly/hiiniafrika or scan the QR Code and register. Tickets are free, however only available to registered individuals, and they will be given on first come first served order. 

You do not want to miss this! We look forward to seeing you next weekend when we will be gracing the stage with  first of its own kind enchanting magnificent Theatre Musical ‘Story Of Africans Told By Africans Themselves! 

With Love From Tanzania❤️🇹🇿! 

#HiiNiAfrikaMusical #TanzaniaToTheWorld #musicaltheatre 

@hiiniafrika @hiiniafrika @hiiniafrika 

#tanzania #daresalaam

Muda umewadia sasa! Na tunafuraha kubwa kuwaletea mchezo wa jukwaa wa kusisimua wa “Hii Ni Afrika” utakaofanyika tarehe 12 na 13 Agosti, katika Makumbusho ya Taifa ya Tanzania (mkabala na Chuo Kikuu Cha IFM Dar es Salaam).

Onyesho hili litafanyika mara mbili kwa siku show ya kwanza ni kwanzia saa 8:00-9:00 mchana na la pili kwanzia saa 1:00-2:00 jioni. Tafadhali tunataarifu kuwa onyesho la tarehe 12 Agosti siku ya Jumamosi la saa 1:00-2:00 jioni litahudhuriwa na walioalikwa tu.

Ticket ni bureee kabisaaa. Pata tiketi yako sasa kwa kupitia link iliyopo kwenye Bio yangu au tuma ujumbe wa jina lako kamili, muda na siku unayopenda kuja kuangalia show kwenda number 0744067433.

🇷🇼 We had the opportunity to visit the Kigali Genocide Memorial, a place that has the purpose of reminding and providing an important lesson for the future. This year marks 29 anniversary of the genocide. The memorial has more than 250,000 bodies in the graves, that were the result from the genocide.

What i have realised is most genocides formula is the same it all starts with the establishment of hate and division, and the rule through biased power structure. Or establishment of identity cards (e.g ethnic or religious), corrupt media, facing ignorance from organizations that are trusted to provide peace and security of people and many more including the massacre.

But what is inspiring is the efforts done to heal and move away from such ignorant and dangerous extremism ideologies. Rwanda has moved on, economically, socially and politically. It has one of the world’s fastest-growing economies, averaging 8% per year over the past decade, according to the International Monetary Fund. The World Bank says Rwanda is the third best place to start a business in Africa, behind Mauritius and South Africa. 

A lot of the changes for Rwanda’s transformation were initiated by President Paul Kagame, who is credited for ending the 1994 genocide and establishing political stability. In 2000, Mr. Kagame’s government crafted a development programme dubbed “Vision 2020” whose goal is to “transform Rwanda from a low-income agriculture-based economy to a knowledge-based, service-oriented economy by 2020.” 

It was a lesson for the future indeed and my respect to Rwanda grew much more.

The Global Citizen Move Afrika movement is a 5-year, large-scale effort to pioneer a first-of-its-kind international music tour throughout the continent of Africa. This annual series of live events will showcase the best of Africa to the world while also driving investments in the communities where they take place, some of it’s goals is to have a social economic impact in Afrika by creating jobs/opportunities for people as well as investing in accessible healthcare, through live music concert.

And I’m glad I got to experience it in Rwanda, the arena was spectacular @bkarenarw It is the biggest indoor arena in East Africa you can clearly see the investment done, and it can hold 10,000 people.
